        <h2>Step 4: Evaluate with structured demos</h2>
        <p>Don't let vendors run generic demos. Before each demo, send the vendor your top 5 pain points and ask them to show specifically how their platform addresses each one. A vendor who can't answer this clearly probably doesn't solve your problems well.</p>

        <h3>Demo red flags</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>The demo is all features and slides, with little actual software shown</li>
          <li>Requests to show specific workflows are deflected to "we'll cover that later"</li>
          <li>The vendor can't explain how the pricing works for your specific situation</li>
          <li>References are stalled or never provided</li>
          <li>Contract terms include auto-renewal with minimal notice period</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Questions to ask every vendor</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>What does implementation typically take, and what's included in the onboarding?</li>
          <li>How does the pricing scale as we add users or projects?</li>
          <li>What happens to our data if we cancel?</li>
          <li>What integrations do you have with [our accounting software]?</li>
          <li>Can you connect us with two references in our specific contractor segment?</li>
          <li>What's your current product roadmap for the next 12 months?</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 5: Run a structured trial</h2>
        <p>Free trials are only valuable if you use them on real work, not toy data. Run your trial on an actual active project — set up the real schedule, enter the real budget, and use the platform for your actual daily workflow for 2–4 weeks. A trial that lives in demo data doesn't tell you how the software performs in real use.</p>

        <p>Include the people who will actually use the software in the trial — not just the decision-maker. Field supers, project managers, and office administrators all have different needs and different tolerances for complexity.</p>

        <h2>Step 6: Evaluate total cost of ownership</h2>
        <p>The subscription price is only part of the cost. Also budget for:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Implementation and setup:</strong> Many platforms charge for onboarding. Even "free" onboarding requires staff time to configure the system.</li>
          <li><strong>Training:</strong> Plan for 2–4 hours per user for basic training, more for power users. This is real labor cost.</li>
          <li><strong>Integration costs:</strong> Connecting to accounting software, payroll, or other systems often requires technical setup and ongoing sync management.</li>
          <li><strong>Productivity dip during transition:</strong> The first 60–90 days on a new system are slower than normal. Budget for this in your capacity planning.</li>
          <li><strong>Annual price increases:</strong> SaaS pricing rarely stays flat. Budget for 5–10% annual increases in your multi-year projections.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 7: Negotiate before signing</h2>
        <p>Construction software vendors — particularly for annual or multi-year contracts — have more pricing flexibility than they initially present. Leverage points include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Annual prepay in exchange for a discount (often 10–20% off monthly pricing)</li>
          <li>Extended trial period before billing starts</li>
          <li>Reduced per-user pricing for volume commitments</li>
          <li>Free or reduced-cost implementation support</li>
          <li>Price lock guarantees for the term of the contract</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 8: Plan the implementation seriously</h2>
        <p>Most software buying failures are implementation failures — not product failures. Companies that don't invest in proper setup, training, and change management abandon software that would have solved their problems if deployed correctly.</p>
        <p>Assign an internal champion who owns the implementation. Set a go-live date. Communicate the change to all affected staff before go-live. Schedule follow-up training at 30 and 60 days. Track adoption metrics — are people actually using it, or falling back to spreadsheets?</p>

